<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06302149 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06302149 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  BALLOON; FALL; SPORT; DEATH; US; FIRST  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A bungee jumping instructor was killed in a weekend leap from a hot airballoon in what an association for the thrill sport today called the firstU.S. bungee death.;   Hal Mark Irish of La Mirada fell more than 60 feet tohis death Sunday after he became detached from his bungee cord during ademonstration south of the Perris Valley Airport and Parachuting Center,authorities said.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  General News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  JUMPER'S FALL FROM BALLOON SEEN AS 1ST U.S. BUNGEEDEATH  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The North American Bungee Association, a trade group that seeks to setsafety standards in the rapidly growing sport, said in a statement thatIrish's death was the first in the United States after more than 500,000jumps.;   The cause of the accident was under investigation.;   But theassociation, which sent engineers to inspect Irish's equipment, said itappeared Irish wasn't insured, didn't have a city permit to jump and wasn'tfollowing the association's safety guidelines.;   Bungee jumpers attachthemselves to a long elastic cord similar to a rubber band and leap fromheights, plunging head first and then bouncing back up as the cord recoils.The sport started about five years ago in New Zealand and has spreadworldwide.;   Enthusiasts say a jump provides a big Adrenalin rush and is safewith proper equipment and training. Critics say the jumping should beregulated or banned because of the potential for tragedy.;   Irish had workedthe Ultimate Jump Company, based in Redondo Beach. The company specializes injumps from hot air balloons, said a man identifying himself only as theowner.;   Irish had been bungee jumping for about six months, making some 20leaps, the man said.;   At about 8:30 a.m. Sunday, Irish was demonstrating ajump from a balloon hovering over a dirt road, police said. Jumpers useballoons because bridges are legally off-limits in California.;   After heleaped from the balloon, Irish's bungee cord extended as normal, but as hebounced back up, he became detached from the cord, said Riverside CountyDeputy Coroner Rick Diaz.;   Irish was taken to the Menifee Valley MedicalCenter in Sun City, where he was pronounced dead about an hour later frommultiple injuries, authorities said.;   Along with Irish's death, otherfatalities have been reported in New Zealand and, as recently as Saturday, inSouth Africa.;   Perris city officials said they would investigate thematter.;   Councilwoman Judith Baitinger said she didn't know people werebungee jumping in Perris.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Perris  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911028  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  394  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday, October 28, 199100302149,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>